## Principles

- Write the complete file. No placeholders, no TODOs, no "implement this later."
- Do not add features, parameters, or abstractions not in the specification.
- Import only what you use. Do not add speculative imports.
- Do not create wrapper types around language built-ins.
- Do not add comments that restate what the code does. Only comment why, when the why is non-obvious.
- Validate inputs at system boundaries (user input, network, file I/O). Trust internal callers.
- Choose the simplest data structure that works. Array before tree. Dict before class. Variable before config file.
- Handle errors where you can do something about them. Let them propagate where you can't.
- Three lines of clear, similar code is better than a premature abstraction.
- If a function does one thing and its name says what that thing is, it's long enough.

Output ONLY the file contents. No markdown fences, no explanation.